---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Why This Matters - USCitizenship2032" description="The case for modernizing U.S. birthright citizenship: why now, why this way, and what is at stake.">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="section-dark py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container text-center max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-gold-500 font-semibold tracking-widest uppercase text-sm mb-4">The Case for Change</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-warm-white mb-6">Why This Matters Now</h1>
      <p class="text-warm-white/80 text-lg">
        The debate is broken. Executive orders get blocked in court. The left fears deportation. The right sees no enforcement. Everyone loses.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Problem -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">The Current System Is Failing Everyone</h2>

      <div class="space-y-10">
        <div class="border-l-4 border-teal-600 pl-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">The legal mess</h3>
          <p class="text-warm-gray leading-relaxed">
            In 2025, executive orders tried to change birthright citizenship. Courts blocked them. The case <em>Barbara v. Trump</em> showed what happens when the rules are not clear: millions of people stuck in limbo while politicians and judges fight it out.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-teal-600 pl-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">The all-or-nothing trap</h3>
          <p class="text-warm-gray leading-relaxed">
            Right now there are only two positions: keep things exactly as they are, or try to change them through executive orders. Neither works. The first ignores that the rest of the world has moved on. The second gets struck down in court and scares people.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="border-l-4 border-teal-600 pl-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">The human cost</h3>
          <p class="text-warm-gray leading-relaxed">
            Children who grow up in American schools, speak English, and know no other home can still face deportation because of their parents' status. At the same time, "birth tourism" is real and it hurts public trust in the system.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Why a Constitutional Amendment -->
  <section class="bg-teal-50 py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Why a Constitutional Amendment?</h2>

      <div class="grid gap-6">
        <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-teal-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">Executive orders can be undone</h3>
          <p class="text-warm-gray leading-relaxed">
            Any executive order on immigration can be reversed by the next president. That is not a solution. It is a pendulum. A constitutional amendment is permanent. It gives families a guarantee that no election can take away.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-teal-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">Regular laws can be challenged</h3>
          <p class="text-warm-gray leading-relaxed">
            Any law Congress passes to change birthright citizenship would be challenged in court under the 14th Amendment. An amendment fixes this by updating the Constitution itself. It is the only path that cannot be overturned.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-teal-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">It requires both sides to agree</h3>
          <p class="text-warm-gray leading-relaxed">
            Passing an amendment requires 2/3 of Congress and 3/4 of state legislatures. That is a feature, not a bug. It means the final version will be tested, debated, and improved by the widest possible group. The result is stronger and more trusted.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-teal-200 p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold mb-2">The 2032 start date gives time</h3>
          <p class="text-warm-gray leading-relaxed">
            By setting the start date to January 1, 2032, the proposal gives years for debate, legal review, and public conversation. No one is rushed. No one is surprised. And no one born before that date is affected.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What Both Sides Get -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-24">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4 text-center">What Each Side Gets That They Cannot Get Now</h2>
      <p class="text-warm-gray text-center mb-12 text-lg">This is not a deal where everyone loses. Both sides gain something they have never been able to get before.</p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div class="bg-charcoal rounded-lg p-8">
          <h3 class="text-warm-white font-bold text-lg mb-4">
            <span class="text-teal-400">For the Right:</span> Real enforcement
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warm-white/60 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            For decades, conservatives have wanted to reform birthright citizenship but had no way to do it legally. Executive orders get struck down. Laws get challenged. This amendment is the only tool that actually works, and it puts the U.S. in line with Japan, Switzerland, and the UK.
          </p>
          <p class="text-warm-white/60 leading-relaxed">
            It ends birth tourism through the Constitution. It builds citizenship on commitment. And it does it through the process the founders designed.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-charcoal rounded-lg p-8">
          <h3 class="text-warm-white font-bold text-lg mb-4">
            <span class="text-gold-400">For the Left:</span> Permanent protection
          </h3>
          <p class="text-warm-white/60 leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The 10-year path writes the Dream Act into the Constitution. No child who grows up in American schools will ever be deported, and no president can undo that with an executive order.
          </p>
          <p class="text-warm-white/60 leading-relaxed">
            The Legacy Shield protects every person born before 2032. The statelessness guarantee makes sure no child is left without a country. And the whole thing replaces fear with permanent, written-down rights.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Bar is High -->
  <section class="bg-charcoal py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="container max-w-3xl text-center">
      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-warm-white mb-6">Yes, the Bar Is High. That Is the Point.</h2>
      <p class="text-warm-white/70 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        A constitutional amendment needs broad support. One party cannot force it through. It has to earn agreement from across the country. And the 2032 timeline gives room to build that agreement the right way, through debate, data, and democratic participation.
      </p>
      <p class="text-warm-white/70 leading-relaxed">
        The 27 amendments that made it into the Constitution changed the country for the better. Ending slavery. Giving women the vote. Equal protection under the law. Each one was hard. Each one was worth it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="container text-center max-w-2xl">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-4">See What We Are Proposing</h2>
      <p class="text-warm-gray text-lg mb-8">
        Four sections. Clear rules. Read the full text with plain-English explanations.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-center">
        <a href="/amendment" class="btn-primary">Read the Amendment</a>
        <a href="/comparison" class="btn-secondary">View Global Comparison</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
